ar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aAt the turn of the new millenium, war, political oppression, desperate poverty, environmental degradation and disasters, and economic underdevelopment are sharply increasing the ranks of the world's twenty million forced migrants. In this volume, eighteen scholars provide a wide-ranging, interdisciplinary look beyond the statistics at the experiences of the women, men, girls, and boys who comprise this global flow, and at the highly gendered forces that frame and affect them. In theorizing gender and forced migration, these authors present a set of descriptively rich, gendered case studies drawn from around the world on topics ranging from international human rights, to the culture of aid, to the complex ways in which women and men envision displacement and resettlement.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aForced migration. 0aWomen immigrants. 0aWomen refugees. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aBoelaert, Marleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCammack, Diana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aColson, Elizabeth, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrawley, Heaven, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDusauchoit, Tine, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aElmadmad, Khadija, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGilad, Lisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGiles, Wenona, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGómez, Inés, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIndra, Doreen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIndra,